by cultural ideas, social practices and shared identities as well as shaped in response to the social and historical conditions at different moments in American history. Analyzing black public opinion on black nationalism and its relationship with class, Austin challenges the commonly held assumption that black nationalism is a lower class phenomenon. In a refreshing and final move, he makes a compelling argument for rethinking contemporary theories of race away from the current fascination with physical difference, which he contends sweeps race back to its misconceived biological underpinnings. Achieving Blackness is a wonderful contribution to the sociology of race and African American Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrocentrismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack MuslimszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack nationalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  aAchieving.  aBlackness.  aStates.  aUnited.  ablack.  acomplexities.  acontext.  aethnicity.  aexamination.  aimportant.  amovements.  anationalist.  aoffers.  arace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081470707440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814763902.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814763902/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13